<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="43" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1773,2013]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1773,1798]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male of 
<taxonomicName box="[428,549,1773,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Oligotomidae" genus="Aposthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Embioptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="problita">
<emphasis box="[428,549,1773,1797]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">A. problita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from congeners by the basal segment of the left cercus being gradually distally expanded but not abruptly lobed, and the absence of an outcurved hook on the left cercus-basipodite. The female body is very dark and shiny except for pale femoral-tibial joints.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
